 Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-29T14:28:58.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828869/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828869/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Warrington Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the average waiting time for A&E patients in Warrington Hospital in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","124488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828870","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-30","<p>The focus of the Building Safety Programme has been to identify residential buildings in England over 18 metres with aluminium composite material cladding that may present a fire hazard. We do not hold information on the numbers of residents in these buildings.</p><p>However, the Government does publish monthly data releases on the progress of the Building Safety Programme which are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme#data-on-the-building-safety-progamme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme#data-on-the-building-safety-progamme</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-30T14:37:54.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828870/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828870/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many people live in tower blocks which have been declared unsafe after failing fire safety safety tests.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","124489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828872","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>NHS England publishes weekly winter situational reports showing the number of ambulances arriving at accident and emergency (A&amp;E) as well as the number of ambulances that have experienced handover delays of 30 minutes or more on arrival. This is published at a trust and national level, not by each individual hospital site and is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/winter-daily-sitreps/winter-daily-sitrep-2017-18-data/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/winter-daily-sitreps/winter-daily-sitrep-2017-18-data/</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-29T12:20:19.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828872/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828872/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Warrington Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many and what proportion of ambulances arriving at Warrington Hospital's A&E department waited more than 30 minutes in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","124490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828873","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>To date, for the 2018/19 funding year, there have been forty-eight requests to disapply the Dedicated Schools Grant conditions of grant in relation to the movement of funding out of the schools block. Nineteen of these requests have since been withdrawn.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-30T17:50:21.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828873/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828873/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828873/answer/previousversion/37872","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to his Answer of 7 December 2018 to Question 117413 on Schools: Finance, how many disapplication requests for the ring-fenced dedicated schools grant his Department received from local authorities for the financial year 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","124491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828874","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Department does not hold this information. Policy responsibility for Personal Care Budgets lies with the Department of Health and Social Care.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-01-29T11:35:09.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828874/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828874/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the average waiting times for money management arrangements for personal care budgets in social care to be put in place by each local authorities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","124492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828875","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-29","<p>Compacts between local authorities and civil society can be an effective means of strengthening partnership working and delivering better outcomes to those in need. It is the responsibility of local authorities to decide whether a local compact would be of value in their area and to ensure that it is complied with where they are put in place. The Government's forthcoming Civil Society Strategy will provide an opportunity to consider practical ways of improving cross sectoral partnerships.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-29T14:29:04.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828875/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828875/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-23","Voluntary Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the extent to which local authorities’ compacts with the voluntary sector are being complied with in practice; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","124493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828877","Home Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The department continually reviews its operation to improve performance and accountability. Customer feedback, including complaints, are taken into account to ensure we offer value for money; which includes improving the services we offer, the quality of the decisions we make and the provision of an excellent customer service.</p><p>Customers are able to contact the Border, Immigration and Citizenship System about their cases through customer contact centres, and members are able to contact the department through MP account management teams.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-29T16:15:36.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828877/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828877/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-23","Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons the named worker system for immigration applications was stopped; and what assessment her Department has made of the effect of that change on the quality of communication with applicants.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","124494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828878","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>NHS England has received allocations under the £1.4 billion made available to implement Future in Mind of £173 million in 2015/16, £262 million in 2016/17 and £262 million in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>The purposes for the use of this expenditure are set out in chapter 2 of Implementing the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health, NHS England 2016. This is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/fyfv-mh.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/fyfv-mh.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-29T17:10:17.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828878/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828878/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Mental Health Services: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the £1.4 billion allocated under the young people’s mental health strategy Future in Mind, how much of that funding for what purposes has been spent in each year since that funding was announced.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","124495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828879","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>NHS England allocated funding of £4.7 million in December 2016 for 2016/17, and £18.6 million between June and December 2017 for 2017/18 through its Perinatal Mental Health Specialist Community Services Development Fund.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England will allocate funding in 2018/19 to those sites that received funding in 2017/18.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-29T17:09:01.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828879/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828879/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the specialist perinatal mental health community services development fund launched in August 2016, if he will provide a detailed breakdown of funds allocated to new or expanded specialist perinatal mental health community teams; and when such funding was received by each such team.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","124496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828881","Home Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>As part of our work to develop a new Serious Violence Strategy the Home Office has considered a range of factors that may be driving increases in serious violence including the role of social media.</p><p>The Home Office is aware that gangs make use of a number of social media platforms to incite violence and taunt rival gangs and we work closely with the police to identify good practice in tackling this issue and to encourage the police to take action. Operation Domain is an ongoing successful Metropolitan Police Service project taking action against gang-related activity online, working with social media companies to remove relevant content.</p><p>The new Serious Violence Strategy will be published early this year.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-01-29T16:00:38.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828881/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828881/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-23","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has made an assessment of the effect of social media on trends in knife crime; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","124497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828882","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>NHS England does not collect data by health condition for recipients of all types of Personal Health Budget (PHB). For example, NHS England does not collect data by health condition for people in receipt of NHS Continuing Healthcare or budgets integrated with social care.</p><p> </p><p>Excluding these types of PHB, in 2016/17 1,037 people had personal health budgets specifically to meet mental health needs.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-29T17:02:11.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828882/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828882/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Mental Illness: Personal Health Budgets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people diagnosed with a severe and enduring mental health problem are in receipt of a personal health budget from NHS England.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","124498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828883","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>The reforms to the Social Fund in 2013 have allowed local authorities in England and the devolved administrations in Scotland and Wales to deliver their own local provision for people who are in need of urgent help.</p><p> </p><p>Our 2014 review published in November 2014 found that local authorities delivered financial and in-kind support more effectively than the previous provision under the Social Fund, and that therefore local authorities are best placed to ensure help is targeted at those who need it most, alongside their other local services. The Department has no further plans to carry out a further assessment.</p><p>Local authorities in England will receive more than £200 billion to deliver these and other community services between 2016-17 and 2019-20, and will have the certainty to plan ahead through our four-year funding settlement.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-29T17:31:29.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828883/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828883/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect on levels of financial and in-kind support provided to low-income families in different local authority areas of the devolution of control over the Social Fund; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","124499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828884","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-30","<p>‘Housing Benefit Stop Notice’ is an automated system that electronically sends these notices to the Local Authorities. Notices are sent via this process at nil cost. The number of notices sent is recorded in each case, but not in a form that can be aggregated across all cases to provide the information requested.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-30T12:24:40.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828884/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828884/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Universal Credit: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, including errors and duplicates, what the average number of notices is that his Department has sent to local authorities for each person transferring from housing benefit to universal credit; and what estimate his Department has made of the cost of sending such notices to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","124500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828885","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>Following the introduction of the Health and Social Care Act 2012, every local authority has a statutory duty to commission a local Healthwatch service. There are 152 local Healthwatch services in England.</p><p> </p><p>They are independent organisations based in local communities, working with other services to understand people’s health and social care experiences. By listening to local consumers and making sure that their opinions are shared with those who plan and run health and social care services, it allows local communities to help shape the care they receive.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-29T12:32:37.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828885/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828885/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many local authorities have established service user forums under the provisions of the Care Act 2014.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","124501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828886","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>​We are closely following the latest developments in Afrin. Arms exports to Turkey, like all other countries, are subject to export controls. Applications are considered on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, known as the Consolidated Criteria. Decisions are based on the most up-to-date information and analysis available, including reports from our overseas network and military contacts. The Consolidated Criteria provide a thorough risk assessment framework and require us to consider the impact of providing equipment and its capabilities. We do not issue export licences where, for example, we assess there is a clear risk that the goods might be used for internal repression or used aggressively against another country. We keep our approach to all countries under continual review.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-01-31T17:08:30.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828886/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828886/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","Turkey: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to monitor the use of military equipment provided by the UK to Turkey; and what information he holds on whether such military equipment is being used as part of that country's assault on Afrin.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","124502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828888","Home Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Home Office is aware that gangs make use of a number of social media platforms to incite violence and taunt rival gangs and we work closely with the police to identify good practice in tackling this issue and to encourage the police to take action. Operation Domain is an ongoing successful Metropolitan Police Service project taking action against gang-related activity online, working with social media companies to remove relevant content.</p><p>The Government has been clear that social media companies should be going further and faster when taking down content. Ultimately, this material should not be made available in the first place. I intend to meet these companies in due course.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-01-29T16:33:06.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828888/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828888/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-23","Crime: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with representatives from (a) Facebook, (b) Google/YouTube, (C) Twitter, (d) Snapchat and (e) other social media platforms on tackling the prevalence of videos and other forms of social media content that glorify gang and knife crime.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","124503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828889","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-30T15:01:06.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828889/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828889/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-23","War Widows: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) men and (b) women widowed during the Second World War are claiming war widow or widower pensions.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828890","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>The Department’s statutory safeguarding guidance, ‘Keeping children safe in education’ (KCSIE) states that all schools should have appropriate filters and monitoring systems in place to safeguard children from harmful material online.</p><p>All schools must have a behaviour policy, including measures to prevent all forms of bullying. Government funded The UK Safer Internet Centre to develop cyberbullying guidance for schools and an online safety toolkit. The Department is providing £1.6 million of funding for four anti-bullying organisations to support schools to tackle bullying, all include cyberbullying as an integral element.</p><p>The National Curriculum for computing covers e-safety including using technology safely, recognising inappropriate conduct and how to report concerns.</p><p>The Department has legislated to make relationships education (primary level) and relationships and sex education (secondary level) mandatory in all schools, in the future. We expect young people to be taught about positive, healthy relationships and keeping themselves safe in a variety of situations, including online.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-30T17:09:08.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828890/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828890/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828890/answer/previousversion/37874","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Schools: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to promote digital safety in (a) primary and (b) secondary schools to tackle (i) cyber-bullying and (ii) online grooming.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","124505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828891","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-02","<p>We anticipate that the committee will report back to us by spring this year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-02-02T11:00:12.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828891/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828891/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-23","Microplastics: Marine Environment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Hazardous Substances Advisory Committee plans to publish its review into the sources of microplastics and the damage caused by microplastics to the marine environment.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","124506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828892","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>Under EU law, UK students have the same access to higher education (HE) as students from the host member states. This means UK students are subject to the same fees, where they are charged, and generally the same loan or support arrangements as nationals of that member state.</p><p> </p><p>Given that financial resources for HE are limited, it is not possible to offer funding for HE study abroad. Funding is focused on eligible students studying within the UK. English domiciled students studying a course at a UK university can receive funding for placements or study abroad where that study comprises less than half of their course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-01-31T15:07:44.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828892/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828892/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Foreign Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of permitting UK students who have been offered a place at a university in an (a) non-UK EU or (b) non-EU country to apply for a student loan.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","124507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828893","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-16","<p>It is long standing Cabinet Office policy not to provide bottled water for meetings.</p><p> </p><p>Bottled water is sold via vending machines and in the local catering outlets in 70 Whitehall.</p><p> </p><p>Information on how much money the department have spent on bottled water is not held centrally and could only be produced at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-16T14:26:29.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828893/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828893/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-23","Cabinet Office: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828895","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-29","<p>We do not hold this information.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-01-29T15:44:32.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828895/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828895/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-23","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828896","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-31","<p>The information requested is not held centrally, and to obtain it would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-31T10:27:15.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828896/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828896/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-23","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828897","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>The department does not purchase bottled water for meetings or water cooler bottles. The water coolers use water which feeds directly from the mains supply.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-31T14:12:33.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828897/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828897/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Department for Education: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828899","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-06","<p>Since 2014, the amount of money spent on purchasing water bottles by Defra’s catering provider has fallen by over a third. Defra as a Department does not purchase any plastic water bottles.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Spend </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2014 - September 2015</p></td><td><p>£7,070.14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2015 - September 2016</p></td><td><p>£4,029.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016 - September 2017</p></td><td><p>£4,481.72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£15,581.57</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The contractor does not hold this level of data for more than 3 years.</p><p> </p><p>The current catering contract expires this summer. The tender for the new contract stipulates that the supplier must not use plastic bottles and single use plastics. Re-usable glasses are now supplied.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-02-06T09:36:50.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828899/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828899/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-23","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828900","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is accommodated in buildings owned by other government departments. The provision of bottled water for meetings is provided by the landlords for each building. There are no specific transactions related to the Department purchasing bottled water detailed in the Department’s central financial system.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2018-01-31T17:45:23.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828900/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828900/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-23","Department for Exiting the European Union: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since its establishment.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828901","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-30","<p>DFID stopped buying bottled water for its UK offices in 2007. Mains-fed water filter units, serving chilled tap water, are installed throughout the UK offices for the use of both staff and visitors. The FCO now manage our overseas offices and are responsible for the provision of supplies, such as bottled water. DFID’s usage will be included in their response for the overall overseas estate to this question. In many countries the mains water is not drinkable and bottled water is provided. However, we do not keep any records of purchases or amounts spent; these are held by the FCO.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-30T16:30:32.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828901/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828901/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-23","Department for International Development: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much money her Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828903","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-30","<p>The department does not purchase bottled water or water cooler bottles, and has not since its establishment. The water coolers use water fed directly from the mains supply.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-01-30T14:51:57.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828903/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828903/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-23","Department for International Trade: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since its establishment.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828904","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-30","<p>The central Department for Transport and the DVLA and VCA executive agencies have not incurred any expenditure on bottled water since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The DVSA and MCA executive agencies have incurred the following expenditure since 2010:-</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£809</p></td><td><p>£3,150</p></td><td><p>£2,819</p></td><td><p>£3,616</p></td><td><p>£1,268</p></td><td><p>£2,675</p></td><td><p>£3,910</p></td><td><p>£4,496</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The vast majority of the spend above has been incurred on the large water dispenser bottles which are used on watercoolers. The empties are returned to the supplier for reuse/refilling.</p><p> </p><p>The spend for one of our Executive Agencies for 2010-11 is not available due to their catering supplier having changed in 2011.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-30T14:55:58.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828904/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828904/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-23","Department for Transport: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828905","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Department introduced a policy several years ago to move away from free standing water chillers with plastic bottles. Instead, where water chillers are required to meet a business need, a plumbed-in supply is normally used.</p><p>There remains a very small number of sites where a plumbed-in supply is not practicable, and in these cases, local arrangements may have been made for water chillers. However, no information is held centrally.</p><p>Prior to the policy change, bottled water would have been provided for business meetings as part of any wider refreshment cost, and cannot be identified separately. Water now provided for official meetings is no longer supplied in plastic bottles; refillable glass bottles or water jugs are provided.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-31T11:41:06.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828905/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828905/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Department for Work and Pensions: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much money her Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828906","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Department has not spent any money on bottled water since 2010 as part of its catering contract. Tap water is provided for hospitality in reusable glass bottles.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-29T12:34:32.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828906/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828906/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-23","Department of Health and Social Care: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828908","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>No information relating to the question is held centrally for years prior to 2016. The below table highlights the available information held on the number of plastic water cooler bottles used by the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office (FCO) UK in calendar years 2016 and 2017.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Quantity</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Size (Ltrs)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Cost</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>1126</p></td><td><p>18.9</p></td><td><p>£8,827.80</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>973</p></td><td><p>18.9</p></td><td><p>£7,628.30</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Water cooler bottles are returned to the supplier for re-use.</p><p>All requests for water coolers are assessed. They are only provided if there is a business need and it is not possible or cost effective to provide a plumbed-in supply. The provision of water coolers is reviewed on a regular basis.</p><p>500ml plastic water bottles are available for staff purchase in the UK from the FCO Catering provider as part of their catering offering, but there is no cost to the FCO. Recycling facilities are provided throughout the FCO to enable staff to recycle these bottles and all other recyclable items.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-31T17:12:53.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828908/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828908/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828909","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-30","The department’s accounting system does not separately identify bottled water spend. This spend falls under the refreshments category and such spending is spread across several account codes.<p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-30T14:15:50.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828909/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828909/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-23","Treasury: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828910","Home Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The majority of water cooler units in the department are now plumbed in and fed direct from the mains water. Hospitality for meetings is provided using glass water jugs which are filled using filtered water.</p><p>However, we have established that a number of HO sites do purchase bottled water for a range of reasons; such as lack of water supply in some very localised areas. We are working to reduce provision of bottled mineral where possible.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-01-31T12:39:59.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828910/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828910/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-23","Home Office: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much money her Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828911","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>The information on how much money was spent on bottled water by the Department, each year since 2010 is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-30T15:04:28.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828911/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828911/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-23","Ministry of Defence: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828912","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-29","<p>The department does not purchase bottled water for meetings or water cooler bottles. The water coolers use water which feeds directly from the mains supply.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-29T16:47:28.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828912/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828912/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828913","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-31","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-01-31T16:04:00.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828913/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828913/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-23","Ministry of Justice: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828915","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>In 2016, the Department spent £54.10 on bottled water, and 2017 £89.70. There are no records held for the previous years.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-01-31T12:23:04.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828915/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828915/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-23","Northern Ireland Office: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how much money her Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828916","Scotland Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Scotland Office does not have any onsite catering or vending facilities. Fresh water supplies are provided directly through fixed water filtration systems which are directly fed from mains water supplies.</p><p> </p><p>We run a number of events, some of which may provide bottled water. However any spend is not recorded separately.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-01-31T12:30:13.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828916/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828916/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-01-23","Scotland Office: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much money his Department has spent on bottled water in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","124526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828917","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>The UK State Pension will remain payable worldwide under domestic legislation following our departure from the EU. We have now reached agreement with the EU to maintain State pension up-rating for those covered by the Withdrawal Agreement. This includes UK nationals living in the EU27 on the specified date or UK nationals who have been subject to the legislation of an EU27 member state prior to the specified date once they reach state pension age even if they are living in the UK on the specified date.</p><p>For UK nationals living in the EU on the specified date this includes people who are already receiving their UK State Pension as well as future UK State Pensioners who have not yet reached State Pension age. We will want to discuss in future talks State Pension up-rating for individuals who are not covered by the Withdrawal Agreement.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-01-29T16:29:11.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828917/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828917/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether UK state pensions will be uprated after the UK leaves the EU for (a) UK citizens of pension age who currently live in an EU country other than the UK, (b) UK citizens of less than pension age who reside in an EU country other than the UK and who intend to retire there and (c) UK citizens who reside in the UK and who intend to retire to an EU country other than the UK in the future.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","124527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828918","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>DWP is fully committed to improving the way customers access the support they need in the simplest way possible. A range of online services are already available and we continue to work directly with the users of our services to understand their needs and build services to meet those needs.</p><p>Although it remains on our longer-term road map, there are no current plans to digitise the process for Personal Independence Payments although we are introducing improved Digital services for the health assessment.</p><p>Similarly, we are not currently planning any digitisation of the Attendance Allowance.</p><p>We have introduced Digital services for a number of our other benefits/ services including Universal Credit, Job Seekers Allowance, Carer’s Allowance, and to support state pensions. We are continuing to prioritise further digital investment for other benefits where we can see improvements for Citizens.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-31T15:03:06.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828918/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828918/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Social Security Benefits: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans her Department has to digitise the application processes for (a) personal independence payments, (b) attendance allowance and (c) other benefits.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","124528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828919","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland intends to meet Love Equality in the coming weeks, subject to diary commitments.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-01-29T16:36:20.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828919/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828919/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-23","LGBT People: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if she will meet representatives of the Love Equality Coalition to discuss moves to improve LGBT rights in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","124529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828921","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>There are no plans to change the application process for Personal Independence Payment or Attendance Allowance as third parties can already assist the claimant throughout the claim process and beyond.</p><p>A third party can assist the disabled person in making the telephone claim for PIP. They can also help the person complete any paper claim form where necessary. Further within the claim process, they can help the claimant complete any evidence gathering forms and can also accompany them to any face to face consultation with a Health Care Professional, at the claimant’s request.</p><p>Separately to this, a third party can make a claim under the Special Rules for the Terminally Ill provisions where the claimant has a life expectancy of less than 6 months, without any involvement from the disabled person, although all notifications are sent to the customer.</p><p>For claims to Attendance Allowance a third party can assist the disabled person by completing a clerical claim form. In addition, claims to Attendance Allowance can be made via Alternative Offices. These are offices authorised by the Secretary of State, with nominated staff trained from specified partner organisations to receive and check Social Security claims made by Attendance Allowance customers. They can also collect and validate information and supporting evidence and record the first date of claim.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-29T15:22:16.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828921/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828921/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Attendance Allowance and Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she plans to change the application processes for personal independence payment and attendance allowance to allow third parties to help claimants.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","124530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828922","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>Information on the reasons looked after children were removed from their placements is published as experimental statistics in the statistical first release <em>‘<em>Children looked after in England including adoption’. </em></em>This information was collected for the first time in 2016 and so comparisons between years should be treated with caution.</p><p> </p><p>The information shows that in 2016, 940 placements in secure units, children’s homes and semi-independent living accommodation were identified as changing because the carer requested the change due to the child’s behaviour. In 2017, this figure was 1,370 but in the same year we saw a drop in placements of that type which ended due to “other” reasons. Feedback from local authorities has identified improved recording of the reasons for placement changes so that more placements are coded under their correct reason rather than “other”. The evidence does not necessarily point to a real increase in the number of placements ending either at the request of the carer due to the child’s behaviour or at the request of the child.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","124544","2018-01-31T14:02:18.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828922/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828922/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Children looked after in England including adoption: 2016 to 2017 statistics published in September 2017, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the number of looked-after children who were removed from their placement at the request of their carer due to their behaviour rose from 940 to 1,370  between March 2016 and March 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","124531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828923","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland has discussed a wide range of issues with the Northern Ireland parties, with the focus of initial engagement being the restoration of a fully functioning Northern Ireland Assembly and Executive.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-01-29T16:37:16.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828923/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828923/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-23","LGBT People: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with representatives of the DUP and Sinn Fein on cross-party attempts to improve LGBT rights in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","124532"
